The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Vipul Infrastructure Developers plans to borrow Rs 500 crore. The company will pay a 7.5 per cent dividend on the paid-up capital. The board has also decided to increase the authorised share capital of the company from Rs 5.15 crore to Rs 15 crore, Vipul has informed stock exchanges. The decisions are subject to shareholders approval, it said. The company will de-list its equity shares from Delhi and Madras stock exchanges.

 AirTel has announced a bouquet of services for the Calcutta telecom circle. It is offering free local calls to any other mobile number for all prepaid customers during the Durga puja at a one-time monthly subscription of Rs 50. Post-paid customers can avail of Talk Festive 200 plan that offers free 300 minutes of local mobile-to-mobile calls, 50 minutes of STD, 50 local SMS at a monthly charge of Rs 200. The offer is valid till November 15.

 Impex group is diversifying into integrated steel manufacturing with the setting up of Ankit Metal and Power Ltd at an investment of Rs 150 crore. The steel plant is located at Jorehira in Bankura. The first phase of the plant is ready and it will produce sponge iron and billets. It will have a captive power plant of 20 mega-watt.

 Gecis Global has been renamed as Genpact. The company is targeting an annual revenue of $1 billion by 2007-08 from its global outsourcing business. The Genpact logo is developed by Interbrand.

 Opus Software Solutions has signed up long-term contracts with 20 mid-sized banks in several East African countries. It is offering them Electra Payment Suit, its payment service solution. The company has revised its revenue target upwards for this fiscal following the encouraging responses from overseas clients.

 Uttam Galva Steels has bagged the Gold Card Holder Status for exports from a consortium of banks under the Gold Card Scheme announced by the Reserve Bank of India. This will help Uttam Galva Steels get a preferential rate of interest on loans from banks.

 Punjab National Bank has merged its three regional rural banks in Punjab ? Gurdaspur Amritsar Kshetriya Gramin Bikash Bank, Gurdaspur Kapurthala Ferozepur Kshetriya Gramin Bank and Kapurthala Shivalik Kshetriya Gramin Bank ? into a new entity called Punjab Gramin Bank.

 JK Corp is hiving off its financial investments into a separate firm to become a pure cement company. The changed identity will be called JK Lakshmi Cements Ltd. The company had initiated its business restructuring in 2000.

